As Debendra Dhinda mentions in their answer, your `Customer` class is not a Spring Component and can therefore not be injected. You can either NOT inject a customer instead create a new Customer in the constructor in the view, or you can add a `@Bean` definition method in your `@Configuration` class. What both approaches have in common is that you call `new Customer()` at some point.

```
// code example for approach 2
@Configuration
public class MySpringConfiguration {

    // this method will be called if you inject/autowire a Customer somewhere.
    @Bean
    public Customer getCustomer(){
        return new Customer();
    }
}
```

