The issue from your code is that, every time `addNewEvent(start,end);` is called you are attaching an on click event handler to `#add_event`.

i.e:

1. The first time `addNewEvent(start,end);` is called, an onclick handler is attached to `#add_event`. When `#add_event` is clicked your operation fires once.
2. The second time `addNewEvent(start,end);` is called, another onclick handler is attached to `#add_event`. When `#add_event` is clicked your operation fires twice.
3. ...this will continue for as long as `addNewEvent(start,end);` is called

Solution:

The onclick handler should be taken out of `addNewEvent(start,end);`. You then attach the event handler once and set new values when `addNewEvent(start,end);` is called

Code:

    $(&#39;#add_event&#39;).click(function(){
        var title = $(&#39;#event_name&#39;).val();
